1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,920
Let's take a look at now how to implement these data structure and techniques in pandas.

2
00:00:04,920 --> 00:00:10,960
We'll start with importing pandas and reading an Excel file that I created for this demo.

3
00:00:11,060 --> 00:00:14,430
This Excel file has multiple sheets that contain

4
00:00:14,430 --> 00:00:17,100
the multiple datasets that we'll be needing for this demo.

5
00:00:17,100 --> 00:00:20,220
I used pandas, read Excel function and specify

6
00:00:20,220 --> 00:00:24,510
the argument sheet name equals none to reading all of these sheets all at once.

7
00:00:24,510 --> 00:00:28,275
I'm then going to assign the result to example data.

8
00:00:28,275 --> 00:00:32,280
Let's go ahead and start with a demo of unpivoting or melting.

9
00:00:32,280 --> 00:00:35,370
I'm going to access the unpivot example sheet in

10
00:00:35,370 --> 00:00:38,850
the example data variable using the sheets name unpivot example.

11
00:00:38,850 --> 00:00:42,620
Then I'm going to make a copy of the DataFrame which we just reviewed as having

12
00:00:42,620 --> 00:00:47,820
column headers as values rather than variable names as the issue for this dataset.

13
00:00:49,310 --> 00:00:52,925
Remember again that the numerical values in the header,

14
00:00:52,925 --> 00:00:56,510
like less than 50 or 50-70 are binned test scores and

15
00:00:56,510 --> 00:01:00,335
the values in the DataFrame are the number of tests that students have taken.

16
00:01:00,335 --> 00:01:03,020
We have the names of the students in the name column.

17
00:01:03,020 --> 00:01:05,545
Here's how we can unpivot this using pandas.

18
00:01:05,545 --> 00:01:09,495
We'll use the melt function with three arguments.

19
00:01:09,495 --> 00:01:14,135
Id_vars is the column to use as the identifier variable.

20
00:01:14,135 --> 00:01:18,410
All columns other than this column are unpivoted to the row axis.

21
00:01:18,410 --> 00:01:23,425
In this example, the name column is the identifier and we want to unpivot the variable,

22
00:01:23,425 --> 00:01:26,195
which is the binned score, and the value,

23
00:01:26,195 --> 00:01:30,325
which is how many tests taken by a student falls within each score range.

24
00:01:30,325 --> 00:01:33,980
Getting to that var_name is how you want to call the new column with

25
00:01:33,980 --> 00:01:37,540
the variables from the original table before the unpivoting.

26
00:01:37,540 --> 00:01:40,720
In this case, we want to call our new variable binned score.

27
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:43,895
Value_name is how you want to call the new column

28
00:01:43,895 --> 00:01:46,880
with the values from the original table before unpivoting.

29
00:01:46,880 --> 00:01:50,285
In this case, we want to call these types of values frequency.

30
00:01:50,285 --> 00:01:52,850
Let's go ahead and run this piece of code.

31
00:01:52,850 --> 00:01:56,310
The result here is our unpivoted DataFrame with three columns,

32
00:01:56,310 --> 00:01:57,890
one of them being the name of the students,

33
00:01:57,890 --> 00:01:59,330
the second being the binned score,

34
00:01:59,330 --> 00:02:01,085
and the third being the frequency.

35
00:02:01,085 --> 00:02:03,170
Let's move to pivoting.

36
00:02:03,170 --> 00:02:07,370
I'm loading my dataset from the pivot example sheet from the same Excel.

37
00:02:07,370 --> 00:02:11,615
Again, recall with this example we have a DataFrame with details on products,

38
00:02:11,615 --> 00:02:13,940
revenue, and the years that we want to have

39
00:02:13,940 --> 00:02:16,790
a better visualization of to understand the groupings.

40
00:02:16,790 --> 00:02:18,880
What do we do here? Well,

41
00:02:18,880 --> 00:02:21,950
what we can do is go ahead and use pandas dot pivot method.

42
00:02:21,950 --> 00:02:24,440
We want to produce groupings for two variables here,

43
00:02:24,440 --> 00:02:27,140
the product classification and the product.

44
00:02:27,140 --> 00:02:31,160
These two variables are what we're specifying as part of our index argument.

45
00:02:31,160 --> 00:02:34,820
Next, we want to see the revenue values per year.

46
00:02:34,820 --> 00:02:37,895
We want the years to be our columns and the values

47
00:02:37,895 --> 00:02:41,695
inside the DataFrame to actually be the actual revenue values.

48
00:02:41,695 --> 00:02:44,630
Take a look at the output here that we get after running this block of

49
00:02:44,630 --> 00:02:48,985
code that we're able to easily interpret through the groupings.

50
00:02:48,985 --> 00:02:52,745
Next, let's go ahead and move on to transposing.

51
00:02:52,745 --> 00:02:56,195
Here, again, I'm loading my dataset from the right Excel spreadsheet.

52
00:02:56,195 --> 00:02:58,070
As we just covered previously,

53
00:02:58,070 --> 00:03:00,780
the student IDs with this dataset are in the header and

54
00:03:00,780 --> 00:03:04,010
subsequent rows have info on students and their test scores.

55
00:03:04,010 --> 00:03:08,840
Let's go ahead and simply transpose the DataFrame using the.T method.

56
00:03:08,840 --> 00:03:12,990
Notice a few things have happened after we're able to do this.

57
00:03:13,880 --> 00:03:18,635
The ID header has actually now become the DataFrame's index.

58
00:03:18,635 --> 00:03:23,060
We also see that students and test score are unfortunately part of the values,

59
00:03:23,060 --> 00:03:25,130
but these should actually be our headers.

60
00:03:25,130 --> 00:03:29,225
How can we keep the ID as our index but reset our header?

61
00:03:29,225 --> 00:03:33,005
We can actually use the.set index on our original DataFrame

62
00:03:33,005 --> 00:03:37,255
with the ID column and then transpose the DataFrame.

63
00:03:37,255 --> 00:03:39,610
Now, the ID, students,

64
00:03:39,610 --> 00:03:44,885
and test score variables are in our header and the ID variable is still our index.

65
00:03:44,885 --> 00:03:47,470
Next, let's go over merging.

66
00:03:47,470 --> 00:03:49,485
With this use case, I first load in

67
00:03:49,485 --> 00:03:52,460
two data tables from two Excel sheets for my example,

68
00:03:52,460 --> 00:03:54,620
data variable around movie reviews.

69
00:03:54,620 --> 00:03:56,990
Again, recall that both tables here have

70
00:03:56,990 --> 00:03:59,660
the same observational unit in individual movie,

71
00:03:59,660 --> 00:04:02,080
but were kept separate due to poor planning.

72
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:06,720
We can merge these two DataFrames using pandas merge method.

73
00:04:07,060 --> 00:04:12,740
Now we can see that the two tables have been merged and we have our review ID,

74
00:04:12,740 --> 00:04:14,750
movie title, viewer, review,

75
00:04:14,750 --> 00:04:17,320
and rating columns all in one table.

76
00:04:17,320 --> 00:04:22,715
By default, merge performs an inner join using intersection of keys from both frames,

77
00:04:22,715 --> 00:04:26,705
in this case the ID column and preserving the order of the left keys,

78
00:04:26,705 --> 00:04:32,035
in this case the ID column from the merging ex_1 table or our first table here.

79
00:04:32,035 --> 00:04:35,405
Let's take a look at another use case for appending.

80
00:04:35,405 --> 00:04:39,905
In this case again, I'm loading in two tables from two Excel sheets.

81
00:04:39,905 --> 00:04:44,180
We want to append the rows of the second table to the first.

82
00:04:44,180 --> 00:04:48,330
We can use pandas concat method specifying the two DataFrames.

83
00:04:48,330 --> 00:04:51,275
We also specify the parameter ignore index

84
00:04:51,275 --> 00:04:54,995
equals true to make sure that the index is labeled 0^n-1,

85
00:04:54,995 --> 00:04:57,770
where n is the total number of rows.

86
00:04:57,770 --> 00:05:00,200
This is so that we don't end up using

87
00:05:00,200 --> 00:05:05,630
the index values along the concatenation access that can be jumbled up during append.

88
00:05:05,630 --> 00:05:07,385
For example, if we run this operation here,

89
00:05:07,385 --> 00:05:10,855
we see a very clean index and both of our two tables appended.

90
00:05:10,855 --> 00:05:13,590
If we don't specify ignore index is equal to true,

91
00:05:13,590 --> 00:05:17,300
we can see here with this example of the index value 0,

92
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:21,605
1, 2 repeating as we have appended the two tables.

93
00:05:21,605 --> 00:05:26,150
Finally, let's conclude this with a group by aggregation example.

94
00:05:26,150 --> 00:05:30,770
We're going to conclude by loading a very simple dataset with the date and score columns.

95
00:05:30,770 --> 00:05:35,450
We're then going to use pandas groupby function to group our dataset by date

96
00:05:35,450 --> 00:05:37,760
while setting this to work parameter to

97
00:05:37,760 --> 00:05:40,505
false so that the order of the DataFrame is preserved.

98
00:05:40,505 --> 00:05:42,665
We want it to be March followed by April,

99
00:05:42,665 --> 00:05:47,335
rather than sorting the group keys so that April comes before March by default.

100
00:05:47,335 --> 00:05:49,125
Now comes the aggregation.

101
00:05:49,125 --> 00:05:51,560
We want to get the sum and mean of values

102
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:54,820
in this score column when we group our dataset by date.

103
00:05:54,820 --> 00:05:56,655
Let's go ahead and run this.

104
00:05:56,655 --> 00:05:59,300
Here we get our result where we can see the sum of

105
00:05:59,300 --> 00:06:02,450
our values in the score column for March and April,

106
00:06:02,450 --> 00:06:05,080
and the mean of these values as well.

107
00:06:05,080 --> 00:06:07,550
This is a foundational example of a groupby,

108
00:06:07,550 --> 00:06:10,040
but there are more parameters and inputs that you can specify

109
00:06:10,040 --> 00:06:13,670
the groupbys and aggregation functions depending on your use case.

110
00:06:13,670 --> 00:06:18,510
This method has a lot of potential to help you better understand your dataset.

